# Backend Code Quality + SOLID

Design predictable services: clear boundaries, explicit contracts, safe failures, and testable logic.

## Core Rules

- Single responsibility per module (router, service, repository, mapper should stay separate).
- Depend on abstractions/interfaces; inject collaborators instead of hard-coding implementations.
- Keep controllers/handlers thin; business rules live in domain/service layer.
- Use composition and small units over monolithic utility files.
- Keep public service contracts explicit and stable (DTOs/schemas/types).

## API and Data Integrity

- Validate and sanitize all external input at boundaries.
- Enforce authn/authz checks at endpoint/service boundaries.
- Use explicit, consistent error mapping (domain -> HTTP/status/error code).
- Never trust client-provided identifiers, roles, or computed totals.
- Keep persistence logic out of handlers; isolate in repositories/data-access layer.

## Reliability and Observability

- Fail loudly with structured logs; do not swallow exceptions.
- Include correlation/request IDs in logs when available.
- Use retries/timeouts/circuit-breaker patterns for unstable downstream calls.
- Make side effects idempotent where practical (especially write endpoints/jobs).

## Maintainability and Testing

- Prefer pure functions for domain logic to simplify testing.
- Add/adjust tests for success, failure, and edge cases when behavior changes.
- Remove dead code and unused endpoints/exports.
- Keep modules cohesive; split files when responsibility grows.

## Quick Examples

```typescript
// BAD: handler contains validation + business logic + persistence
app.post("/orders", async (req, res) => {
  // mixed responsibilities and weak boundaries
});

// GOOD: handler delegates; service coordinates domain logic
app.post("/orders", async (req, res) => {
  const input = validateCreateOrder(req.body);
  const result = await orderService.create(input);
  res.status(201).json(result);
});
```

```typescript
// BAD: swallowed exception
try {
  await repository.save(entity);
} catch (e) {}

// GOOD: structured log + mapped domain error
try {
  await repository.save(entity);
} catch (e) {
  logger.error("Order save failed", { error: e, orderId: entity.id });
  throw new PersistenceError("Could not persist order", { cause: e });
}
```
